    en: "In New York, neither parent has an automatic right to custody. A judge decides based on one question: what is in the best interest of the child. The court looks at many things, like who has been the main caretaker, how stable each home is, and whether either parent has a history of domestic violence. Unmarried parents use Family Court; parents going through divorce use Supreme Court. New York Domestic Relations Law 70 is the main statute. There is no filing fee to start a custody or visitation case in Family Court."
